Aim
To capture live network packets using Wireshark and analyze ICMP packets generated during ping
communication.
Introduction
Wireshark is a network packet analyzer used to capture and inspect network traffic in real time. It helps
analyze protocols, packet headers, source IP addresses, destination IP addresses, and communication
between systems.
ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) is commonly used for network testing through the ping command.
Wireshark is widely used in cybersecurity, network troubleshooting, and packet analysis.
Procedure
Step 1: Install Wireshark
1. Download and install Wireshark on Windows or Kali Linux.
2. Launch the Wireshark application.
Step 2: Select Network Interface
1. Choose the active network interface:
• Wi-Fi
• Ethernet
• VirtualBox Host-Only Adapter (if using VM)
2. Double-click the interface to start packet capture.
Step 3: Generate ICMP Traffic
Open terminal or command prompt and run:
ping google.com
Step 4: Apply ICMP Filter
In Wireshark filter bar, enter:
icmp
Press Enter to display only ICMP packets.
Step 5: Analyze Packets
Observe:
• Source IP address
• Destination IP address
• ICMP Echo Request
• ICMP Echo Reply
• Packet size and time
